---
id: dxos.spec.core
name: DSL.Core
version: 1.0
---

The minimal base language. Defines document format and the `ext` primitive only.
All domain constructs — type, op, feat, test, ui, db, service, etc. — are extensions.

## Document Format

A `.spec` file has three parts:

1. **Frontmatter** — YAML block delimited by `---`. Contains document metadata.
2. **Body** — Standard Markdown prose, headings, and lists.
3. **Blocks** — Typed fenced sections carrying structured declarations.

### Frontmatter

```
id:        URI           # globally unique document identifier
name:      Identifier    # human-readable name
version:   SemVer        # document version
extends?:  URI[]         # specs this document extends (transitive)
```

### Blocks

A block is a fenced section with a declared type, optional identifier, and optional title:

```
```<type> [<id>][: <title>]
...body...
```
```

- `<type>` must be declared in the Extensions section of this document or an ancestor.
- `<id>` is an optional locally-scoped identifier (e.g. `FR-1.1`, `Board`).
- `<title>` is optional human-readable prose after the colon.
- Block identifiers must be unique within the document.

### Block Body Syntax

Within a block, the body is a sequence of key-value pairs:

```
key: value                # scalar
key: a | b | c            # union list (variants)
key?: TypeExpr            # optional field declaration
key:                      # multi-line value
  - item one
  - item two
# comment
```

When an extension declares `inline-prose: true`, the first line may be
bare prose with no key:

```
```feat F-1: Start Game
  A new Board is created with pieces in starting positions.  ← inline prose
  req F-1.1: White moves first.
```
```

### Cross-References

Any declared block identifier may be referenced elsewhere in the document as `[<id>]`.
The linter verifies that all references resolve to a declared block.

---

## Extensions Section

Every document that uses non-core block types MUST declare them:

```
## Extensions

| Term     | URI                        |
|----------|----------------------------|
| `type`   | dxos.spec/ext/type@1.0     |
| `feat`   | dxos.spec/ext/feat@1.0     |
```

An extension definition is either:
- **External** — resolved by URI (registry lookup, future tooling).
- **Inline** — defined in the document's Appendix using `ext` blocks.

A document may use both: external URIs for standard extensions,
inline `ext` blocks for custom or experimental ones.

---

## The `ext` Primitive

`ext` is the only block type the core language natively provides.
It is self-describing — defined here using itself:

```ext ext
  uri: dxos.spec.core/ext
  desc: Declares a new block type or extends an existing one.
  fields:
    uri:            URI           # canonical identifier for this extension (required)
    desc:           Prose         # human description (required)
    extends?:       ExtRef        # parent extension — inherits all parent fields
    fields?:        FieldMap      # fields valid on instances of this block type
    adds-fields?:   FieldMap      # additional fields merged into parent (use with extends)
    nesting?:       self | none   # whether instances may contain same-type blocks
    inline-prose?:  Boolean       # first non-key line treated as prose value
    syntax?:        CodeBlock     # reference syntax (non-normative)
    example?:       CodeBlock     # usage example (non-normative)
```

---

## Primitive Types

The following types are available in `ext` field declarations.
They are the vocabulary of the meta-language.

| Type         | Description                                                  |
|--------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|
| `Prose`      | Free-form text, single or multi-line                         |
| `Identifier` | Alphanumeric name, hyphens allowed — e.g. `Board`, `FR-1`   |
| `URI`        | Dot-path or URL identifier — e.g. `dxos.spec/ext/type@1.0`  |
| `SemVer`     | Semantic version string — e.g. `1.0.0`                      |
| `Boolean`    | `true` or `false`                                            |
| `TypeExpr`   | Type reference or inline type — e.g. `Color`, `Piece?`       |
| `FieldMap`   | Named fields: `name[?]: TypeExpr  # comment`                 |
| `UnionList`  | Pipe-separated variants: `a \| b \| c`                       |
| `ProseList`  | Bulleted list of prose items                                 |
| `CodeBlock`  | Literal indented or fenced text                              |
| `ExtRef`     | Reference to a declared extension name                       |
| `TagList`    | Space or comma-separated tag identifiers                     |

---

## Resolution Rules

1. When a block type appears in a document body, the linter looks it up
   in the nearest enclosing Extensions table (this document or any ancestor).
2. If the URI resolves to an inline `ext` block in an Appendix, that definition is used.
3. If the URI is external, the linter fetches the definition from a registry.
4. An unresolvable block type is a lint error.
5. Field names not declared in the `ext` definition are lint warnings.

---

## Non-Goals

The core language deliberately omits:

- Execution semantics — `.spec` is a specification, not a program.
- Type checking — field values are not verified against TypeExpr at the core level.
- Ordering constraints — sections may appear in any order.
- Verification — requirements are semi-formal; the language is not a proof system.
